<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Dr Jennifer Colman MA, LMSSA, LLM</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Written evidence from Dr Jennifer Colman supported by her Member of Parliament Mr George Freeman MP (GMC0004)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Introduction</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Dr Jennifer Colman is registered and licensed with the GMC. She was an elected medical member of the GMC, for the English constituency, from 27 April 2000 to 30 June 2003 and also a charity trustee of the organisation. She has also been called to the Bar and holds licensed access from the BSB. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#2a2a2a; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#2a2a2a; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">SUBJECT: GENERAL MEDICAL COUNCIL and THEIR BREACH OF HUMAN RIGHTS</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Executive Summary</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A number of the GMC disciplinary and administrative procedures are non compliant with Human Rights.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The GMC fails to give full discovery of documents in respect of doctors under investigation and in that is in breach of Article 6 and the right to a fair trial</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The GMC fails in its data processing of doctor’s disciplinary records and is in breach of Article 8 (1), the right to a private and family life and the disciplinary records of doctors.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The GMC fails to comply with Rehabilitation over criminal offences and in doing so is out of step with Rehabilitation for criminal offences in general and the Criminal Records National Data Base and is therefore also in breach of Article 8.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Article 6 and Discovery of documents</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">When a doctor is faced with proceedings against him/her at the GMC they can face an insurmountable hurdle over discovery. In short the GMC often fails to give a full discovery on time or at all. This can happen whether or not the doctor is represented by a defence body. A doctor without representation will have to rely as best he can on the use of subject access requests under the Data Protection Act to obtain discovery. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Information Commissioner found the GMC to be non compliant with the Data Protection Act in 2002 [1] and 2004 [2]. Although it is to be hoped that the GMC is now compliant their non compliance with the DPA and discovery has been fatal to doctors who could have successfully appealed in the past. It is notable that no disciplinary papers were forthcoming as a result of the two subject access requests made by the doctor alone which led to the findings against the GMC in 2002 and 2004. The main problem for a doctor using the process of a subject access request is that there is always an incomplete discovery and the GMC may use their discretion in interpreting the Data Protection Act and withhold vital information.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In 2005 the same doctor who made the 2002 and 2004 subject access requests used solicitors to obtain a very limited discovery of disciplinary papers through a further subject access request. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As a result legal proceedings were issued which eventually led to a fuller discovery by a Court Order of Sir John Thomas and Dame Janet Smith LLJs on 17 June 2009 when they gave leave under exceptional circumstances for judicial review of the GMC. At that time they said of erasure from the medical register:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“It is also plain that so serious a sanction taken against a professional individual as erasure from the medical record is of such a nature that, if injustice was done, however long ago, it is time that it was remedied. Delay cannot be an excuse for failing to do that. None of the delay, it seems has arisen as a result of the fault of the applicant.”   </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">[3]</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In spite of a much fuller discovery arriving at the end of July 2009 there has never been a full discovery in this case. However the importance of discovery is illustrated in the above case when the documents arrived which showed that the GMC admitted in their internal papers at the time of the doctor’s disciplinary hearing that they had inserted inadmissible evidence which had been aired publicly at the hearing and that the doctor had grounds for appeal. It is unfortunate that the GMC remained silent at the time and in the following years, and if not for the Lord Justices Order in 2009 the doctor would still not know the extent of the chance she had lost to clear her name. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The GMC might say it is not obliged to help any doctor by revealing evidence which would aid the doctor’s case or aid them in an appeal especially if that would cast doubt on the GMC’s own processes. That must be wrong, unprincipled and show a total disregard for a just process and outcome. The GMC states that it is not there to punish a doctor but </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to protect the public. By concealing evidence which would lead to a doctor being able to appeal successfully then the GMC is in fact punishing the doctor. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Article 8 (1) of the Human Rights Act and the GMC’s Data Base of findings against the doctor</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The GMC maintains a data base of doctors’ past adverse findings in matters of conduct and also the doctors’ criminal convictions. This data base is also kept in the Statutory Libraries. The Statutory Libraries are transferring all their data onto web based data bases. This runs the increased risk of details about any doctor being widely disseminated long after the event as well as members of the public accessing the data from the paper data. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.67pt; padding-left:1.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Rehabilitation of Findings for Misconduct</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The GMC fails to place a rehabilitation time on findings for misconduct against any doctor. This is wrong, disproportionate and in breach of Article 8(1) of the Human Rights Act. There should be rehabilitation times which vary according to the sentence imposed by the GMC.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Moreover if a doctor is erased from the register then there should be a maximum period of 5 years after which the doctor ought to be considered to have been rehabilitated. Restoration cannot be achieved in less than five years if at all, and is unlikely to be achieved after a further five years, in which case no useful purpose is served by the conduct matter remaining on record. Moreover the doctor will likely have his misconduct displayed on the internet and disadvantage and damage continues to the doctor who seeks other work. Employers scour the internet for information about those seeking employment. Often the doctor cannot find employment in any other sphere and the intention does appear that the GMC will have acted to ensure that a number of doctors are forced onto the margins of society and into penury and onto benefits.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Once a doctor dies then his record should die with him but it does not. If it does not then future generations of his family will be reminded from time to time about his record. It will always be a matter of public record if someone chooses to dig around and parade it publicly. It is unfair for a family to suffer because of a family member, who may well have been a reasonable doctor up until the event or events which led to his disciplinary </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">hearings and findings against him. He may also have been a good family member and his record can only add to the overall hurt of the family.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">By maintaining this data base the GMC is in breach of Article 8(1) of the Human Rights Act which provides for the “Right to respect for private and family life” and states:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 72pt 12pt 86pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Everyone has the right to respect for his private . . . life . . . </span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">     Article 8(2) states:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 72pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2   There shall be no interference by a public authority with the exercise of this right except such as is in accordance with the law and is necessary in a democratic society in the interests of national security [or] public safety . . . for the prevention of disorder or crime, . . . or for the protection of the rights and freedoms of others.</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The material held in the GMC data base is of a personal and private nature and that its retention is unlawful because it involves an interference with the doctor’s right under Article 8(1) to respect for their private lives which cannot be justified.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Art 8(2) does not justify interference by storing the older data beyond what is suggested above as a rehabilitation period and therefore it cannot overcome the Art 8(1) argument. We rely on the arguments advanced in the recent case of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">The Queen on the Application of John </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Oldroyd</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline"> Catt v (1) The Association of Chief Police Officers of England, Wales and Northern Ireland and ors</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> [2012] EWHC 1472 (Admin) discussed below. [4]</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:1.8pt"><tr><td style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:451.8pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; text-decoration:underline">Article 8(1) Right to a private life</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:451.8pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr></table><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> The Court stated in [4] that information of a public nature, such as a conviction, may become private over the course of time as memories fade, thereby enabling people to put their past behind them and the storage and use of personal information that has been gathered from open sources (e.g. public observation, media reports etc.) may involve an infringement of a person’s rights under article 8(1) if it amounts to an unjustified interference with his personal privacy.  This is different from the way in which the GMC retains and disseminates personal data about doctors. Because the GMC appears to operate outside lawful and ethical rules with respect to doctor’s data it is more difficult, even impossible, for doctors to put their past behind them.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is notable that the GMC is prepared and does “sell off” a doctor’s disciplinary transcripts to anyone for a fee. They do so without asking the doctor who was the subject of the disciplinary hearings whether they object. This has resulted in one particular doctor obtaining transcripts and subsequently hoisting them on her well known internet sites whilst adding her own often adverse comments. Unlike the court system where anyone requesting a transcript of a hearing would likely be refused or have to show “due cause” for their request, the GMC does none of this. In particular one restored and therefore registered doctor’s old transcripts were sold by the GMC to another doctor, who then with a second doctor quoted from them on the BMJ’s own Rapid Responses website, causing alarm and distress to the restored and registered doctor who recognised that the transcripts must have been sent out from the GMC. Later data recovery of letters from the GMC showed that the GMC had sold these transcripts over a period of two years whilst realising that the transcripts were being quoted by the purchaser on the BMJ’s website giving a view that the previously disciplined doctor was an unfit person. Subsequently the purchaser sent copies of the BMJ’s website to his own MP and the then Minister of Health claiming that the doctor was unfit and the BMJ’s website was evidence of that. Subsequently the purchaser admitted in writing to the BMJ that their aim was to have the registered doctor removed from the medical register. The original BMJ’s Rapid Responses postings remain on the website and stored in other data bases at home and abroad. Our position is that this shows that the GMC is an unfit organisation to retain sensitive data which they may then use in ways to continue to punish the doctor.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Court stated that it had defined the concept of “private life” as a broad term not susceptible to exhaustive definition. It covers:   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The physical and psychological integrity of a person and can therefore embrace multiple aspects of the person's physical and social identity.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Gender identification, name and sexual orientation and sexual life fall within the personal sphere protected by art.8. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Beyond a person’s name, his or her private and family life may include other means of personal identification and of linking to a family.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(d)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Information about the person’s health is an important element of private life.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(e)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> An individual’s ethnic identity must be regarded as another such element. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(f)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> A right to personal development, and the right to establish and develop relationships with other human beings and the outside world. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(g)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The concept of private life includes elements relating to a person’s right to their image.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 11.35pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Court also said that the mere storing of data relating to the private life of an individual amounts to an interference within the meaning of art.8. The subsequent use of the stored information has no bearing on that finding. In determining whether the personal information retained by the authorities involves any of the private-life aspects mentioned above, there must be regard to the specific context in which the information at issue has been recorded and retained, the nature of the records, the way in which these records are used and processed and the results that may be obtained.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 11.35pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Interference with the right to respect for private life may be justified if it is in accordance with        the law and necessary in a democratic </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">society in the interests of various beneficial aims which are conducive to the well-being of society as a whole.  In order to justify an interference with article 8(1) rights the GMC must demonstrate that the conduct in question satisfies three requirements:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 85.05pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">i)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that it is in accordance with the law;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 85.05pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">ii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that it is carried out in pursuit of a legitimate aim; and</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 85.05pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">iii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that the interference is proportionate to the aim sought to be achieved.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Once a doctor’s case has concluded then the legitimate aim of protecting the public has been satisfied.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The question of legality and proportionality are best considered in the context of individual cases, for instance where a doctor has been disciplined for viewing, storing and or distributing child porn, and remains on the register. In such a case, and if there has been a conviction then the Police Data Base will keep the record as will the Sex Offenders Register and the Criminal Records National Data Base. Under the circumstances it is difficult to see why the GMC would also need to keep the record beyond five to ten years. If there has been no conviction then the GMC may decide that they need to keep the data as the doctor may be involved in the care of vulnerable young people. In any event it should be proportionate.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The overriding principle is the need to strike a fair balance between the personal interest of the doctor in maintaining respect for his private life and the pursuit of a legitimate aim in the interests of the public at large. In order to justify the collection, processing and retention of personal information the GMC must be able to satisfy the doctor that each of those steps is governed by clear rules of law or policy which are both accessible and intelligible and do not give the GMC an excessively broad discretion over the manner of their implementation. At the moment there seems to be a much broader discretion which is both unreasonable and unjustified.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In all cases it is therefore necessary for the GMC to pay careful attention to the nature of the information in question, the circumstances under which it can be obtained, the ways in which it can be processed and by whom, the period for which it can be retained (together with any arrangements for interim review) and the arrangements for its destruction. The GMC does none of this.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> It must be for the GMC to justify its need under Article 8(2) to retain a doctors’ data after 5 years.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34pt; padding-left:2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Rehabilitation of Criminal Convictions which remain on the doctor’s GMC record</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The GMC fails to operate any rehabilitation process as far as criminal convictions are concerned and the GMC record continues to show that doctors have been found guilty of criminal convictions which are listed. The record shows not only the original charges brought by the GMC against the doctor but the findings also.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">That means that it disregards the Rehabilitation of Offenders Act 1974 and subsequent legislation.. An anomaly exists whereby the GMC is permitted to act outside, and differently from, the legal norm for old criminal convictions. A professional in any other job, for instance a judge and a previous DPP (unnamed here though previously reported in the media), will be rehabilitated but a doctor will never be.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Once a person is rehabilitated then they may lawfully claim under section 4 of the Rehabilitation of Offenders Act 1974 that they have no convictions. However the double standard at the GMC remains because of the refusal to implement the Rehabilitation Act for criminal convictions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Moreover, there can be a substantial difference in the type of conviction and the length of time for rehabilitation. Where minor driving convictions have been long spent, they should remain a private matter.  The GMC is in breach of Article 8 rights to a private life, by keeping these convictions on their record and by ensuring that record is lodged in the Statutory Libraries where members of the public have access.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Having regard to the case of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline"> The Queen on the Application of T v (1) Chief Constable of Greater Manchester and ors </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">[ 2013] EWCA </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Civ</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> 25</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, [5], the GMC should use the exact time limits on rehabilitation of convictions that the Rehabilitation of Offenders Act sets down. If there is no rehabilitation for a conviction and sentence then the GMC cannot be criticised.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This retention of criminal records by the GMC is disproportionate and unnecessary as criminal convictions will be kept on the Criminal Records National Data Base and will be disclosed when a doctor is required to produce a certificate from the Criminal Records National Bureau at the time of being offered a job. At the moment and because the GMC keeps records of criminal convictions on their data bases and in the Statutory Libraries a doctor is treated less favourably than the lay person with similar and same convictions. The doctor is never rehabilitated.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">On 22 October 2010, the Criminal Records Review was established, whose terms of reference were summarised as follows:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2.85pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">    “The Criminal Records Review will examine whether the criminal records regime strikes the </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 5.65pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">    right balance between respecting civil liberties and protecting the public. It is expected to make   </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">            proposals to scale back the use of systems involving criminal records to common sense levels.”</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As a result of the review there have been changes which enable rehabilitated persons to </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">re-establish their lives, in a way that doctors are unable to.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In both case [4] and [5] the issue of Article 8(1) rights was considered to be of such interest and seriousness that the Equality and Human Rights Commission and Liberty acted as Interveners. The GMC is also such a case that the Health Committee is asked to consider making recommendations for change.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There is no guarantee that if the GMC continues to keep a record of doctor’s criminal offences then they would do so in a way which is consistent, fair and in keeping with Human Rights legislation, and after the fashion of Criminal Records Review. Under the circumstances the GMC should be prevented from keeping any data on doctors’ criminal records. We would ask that the Health Committee recommends that the Law Commission considers these breaches and poor practises by the GMC in their current review of the Statutory provisions governing the GMC.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">[</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1] Information Commissioners Letter of findings against the GMC dated 29 May 2002</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">[2] Information Commissioners Letter of findings against the GMC dated 15 May 2004</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">[3] </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">The Queen on the Application of Colman v GMC  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">[2009] EWCA </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Civ</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> 746 </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">[4] </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">The Queen on the Application of John </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Oldroyd</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline"> Catt v (1) The Association of Chief Police Officers of England, Wales and Northern Ireland and ors</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> [2012] EWHC 1472 (Admin). </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">[5] </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">The Queen on the Application of T v (1) Chief Constable of Greater Manchester and ors </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">[ 2013] EWCA </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Civ</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> 25</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>